As Figure \ref{Fig:1} suggests (and as was recently reported by \citet{Fialkov:2014N}), the saturated heating assumption may be justified only in the case of high $f_X$ (green lines in the Figure) where the IGM is indeed hotter than the CMB at the beginning of the EoR. In other  cases the gas is colder than the CMB at the beginning of reionization and undergoes the heating transition during the EoR.  The most interesting case is that of massive halos, which is also well-motivated by the low optical depth measurements. For this star formation scenario  heating is slower than reionization and the neutral gas is always colder than the CMB  in two out of six cases, namely the case of hard X-ray sources  with standard and low heating efficiency.





\section{Extracting the Neutral fraction from the global 21-cm signal} 
